I have formulated a new cognitive hypothesis and implemented the corresponding PyMC model.

Here is the cognitive hypothesis:
> People evaluate the randomness of a sequence strictly based on the absolute number of heads it contains. Their choice between sequences is driven by a cumulative normal (probit) discrimination process on the difference in head counts, reflecting Gaussian internal noise with no baseline rate of random guessing.

This is a specific refinement of the prior "absolute_heads_lapse" hypothesis. By removing the lapse rate and changing the error function from logistic to probit (Gaussian noise), it offers a mathematically distinct, more parsimonious functional form that eliminates random guessing parameters altogether. Through testing, this simple structural change explains the data better (improving the ELPD-LOO) by correctly predicting that errors only happen at small `h_a - h_b` differences without implying a constant baseline lapse rate at larger differences.

The model is successfully created in `candidate.py` and passes the required validation checks. All self-checks report success.
